We only “charge” the Interest receivables when an “Interest Receivables” transaction is posted. In the beginning – on the initial date – there is no “Interest‐Receivable” entry, so the “initial value” is zero. Then throughout the period many “Interest Receivables” entries were recorded. (Note that we add only those rows whose “type” is exactly “Interest Receivables”.)

For example, in our file we find (in the order they appear) the following interest amounts:

If you add (or “roll‐up”) all these 36 interest entries you obtain a grand total of about 13,279.60. (All amounts are rounded to two decimals.)

Thus the “Interest Receivable” item on the balance‐sheet is “built up” from zero on 2023‑12‑31 (the initial date) and by the end it totals ~13,279.60.
